<section id="intro" class="chapter">
    <h2>1. Introduction: Drivers of the Blitzed Nation</h2>
    <p>
        While the bombs rained down and factories roared day and night, Britain depended on its lorry drivers.  
        Whether hauling munitions from Midlands factories, delivering rations across blacked-out London, or  
        navigating the narrow lanes of the countryside, British drivers formed a vital link in the nation’s  
        survival and eventual victory.
    </p>
    <div class="illustration">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a2/Bedford_QL_Truck.jpg" alt="Bedford QL">
        <p><em>The Bedford QL: Icon of British wartime logistics.</em></p>
    </div>
</section>

<section id="vehicles" class="chapter">
    <h2>2. Vehicles of the British Supply Corps</h2>

    <h3>Bedford QL Series</h3>
    <p>Used extensively throughout the war, known for reliability and good handling in tight British roads.</p>
    <div class="illustration">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/43/Bedford_QL_Fuel_Tanker.jpg" alt="Bedford QL Tanker">
    </div>

    <h3>Austin K Series</h3>
    <p>A versatile mid-war truck used for general haulage, troop movement, and radio van conversions.</p>

    <h3>Morris Commercial C8</h3>
    <p>Light and agile, these served convoy escorts, radio units, and artillery towing.</p>
</section>

<section id="routes" class="chapter">
    <h2>3. Strategic Routes & Wartime Conditions</h2>

    <h3>Convoying Through the Blitz</h3>
    <p>Drivers ran blackout routes through shattered cities, guided by dimmed headlamps and firewatch wardens.</p>

    <h3>Rural Ration Runs</h3>
    <p>Delivering food and fuel to distant farms and depots required careful navigation of twisting lanes.</p>

    <div class="illustration">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/f9/London_Blitz_St_Paul%27s.jpg" alt="Blitz London">
    </div>

    <h3>Ports & Overseas Staging</h3>
    <p>South-coast harbors swarmed with drivers transporting material for North Africa, Italy, and D-Day.</p>
</section>

<section id="safety" class="chapter">
    <h2>4. Safety, Blackouts & Civil Defence Rules</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Blackout curtains</strong> mandatory on all cabs.</li>
        <li><strong>Tire conservation</strong> crucial due to rubber shortages.</li>
        <li>Carry <strong>gas masks</strong> at all times.</li>
        <li>Observe <strong>air-raid sirens</strong> and depot security regulations.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="illustration">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/58/WWII_Blackout_Poster_British.jpg" alt="Blackout poster">
    </div>
</section>

<section id="maintenance" class="chapter">
    <h2>5. Depot & Roadside Maintenance</h2>
    <p>British lorrymen were expected to perform their own emergency repairs during rationing and shortages.</p>

    <h3>Common Problems</h3>
    <p><strong>Fuel contamination:</strong> Drain water and grit from tank sediment bowl.</p>
    <p><strong>Electrical faults:</strong> Dynamo brushes often required field cleaning.</p>
    <p><strong>Cold starts:</strong> Use pre-heaters or warm blankets around carburetors.</p>
</section>

<section id="life" class="chapter">
    <h2>6. Life on the Road: Tea, Convoys & Stiff Upper Lips</h2>
    <p>From makeshift tea stoves in cab corners to humorous signs on lorry backs, British drivers built their own  
       culture of resilience and fellowship amid hardship.</p>

    <blockquote>
        “Keep calm, keep driving, and mind the blackout.”  
        — Anonymous RASC Driver, 1941
    </blockquote>

    <div class="illustration">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/0a/ATS_Lorry_Driver_WWII.jpg" alt="ATS Lorry Driver">
        <p><em>Women of the ATS also served as skilled drivers.</em></p>
    </div>
</section>

